    "phases_completed": ["ANCHOR", "ENRICH", "EXPAND", "TRAVERSE_DRUGS", "TRAVERSE_TRIALS", "VALIDATE"],
    "answer_summary": "Globotriaosylceramide (Gb3, also called ceramide trihexoside or GL-3) accumulates in Fabry disease due to deficient or absent alpha-galactosidase A (α-Gal A) enzyme activity, encoded by the GLA gene on Xq22.1. This lysosomal hydrolase normally cleaves the terminal alpha-galactosyl moieties from Gb3 and related glycosphingolipids. Loss-of-function mutations in GLA prevent this catabolic step, causing progressive Gb3 accumulation in lysosomes of vascular endothelium, renal podocytes, cardiomyocytes, and neurons."
  },
